n[99]`.\\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ and $in[i+1]$.\\n   - `out_both[i] = in[i] & in[i+1]` for $i \\neq 99$.\\n   - `out_both[99] = 1\'b0`.\\n   - A clean way to write this in SystemVerilog is using concatenation and selection, or by generating the required signals.\\n\\n2. **`out_any` Logic:** Each bit `out_any[i]` indicates if `in[i]` OR its neighbor to the right (`in[i-1]`) are \'1\'. (Example: `out_any[2]` checks `in[2]` OR `in[1]`).\\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ and $in[i-1]$.\\n   - For $i=1$ to $99$: `out_any[i] = in[i] | in[i-1]`.\\n   - For $i=0$: The neighbor to the right (`in[-1]`) doesn\'t exist, so `out_any[0] = 0`.\\n\\n3. **`out_different` Logic:** Each bit `out_different[i]` indicates if `in[i]` is different from its neighbor to the left (`in[i+1]`), wrapping around. (Example: `out_different[98]` checks $in[98] \\neq in[99]$).\\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ XOR $in[i+1]$.\\n   - For $i=0$ to $98$: `out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[i+1]`.\\n   - For $i=99$ (wrap-around): The neighbor to the left is $in[0]$. So, `out_different[99] = in[99] ^ in[0]`.\\n\\n**Implementation Strategy:**\\nSince all required operations are purely combinational, we will use `assign` statements for maximal efficiency and clarity.\\n\\n**Syntax Error Advice:**\\n- **Array Indexing:** Be careful with array indexing when defining relationships. For example, `in[i+1]` must be valid. Since $i$ goes up to 99, $i+1$ can reach 100, which is out of bounds for `in[99:0]`. This is why we must explicitly handle the boundary conditions (i=99 for `out_both` and i=0 for `out_any`).\\n- **Concatenation vs. Slicing:** The hint warns against reverse slicing (`x[1:2]`). We will use direct indexing or concatenation `{in[i], in[i+1]}` if needed, but direct indexing is simplest here.\\n\\n**Refining Boundary Conditions for Code:**\\n\\n*   `out_both[99] = 1\'b0;`\\n*   `out_any[0] = 1\'b0;`\\n*   `out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[(i+1) % 100];`