n[99]`.\\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ and $in[i+1]$.\\n   - `out_both[i] = in[i] & in[i+1]` for $i \\neq 99$.\\n   - `out_both[99] = 1\'b0`.\\n   - A clean way to write this in SystemVerilog is using concatenation and selection, or by generating the required signals.\\n\\n2. **`out_any` Logic:** Each bit `out_any[i]` indicates if `in[i]` OR its neighbor to the right (`in[i-1]`) are \'1\'. (Example: `out_any[2]` checks `in[2]` OR `in[1]`).\\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ and $in[i-1]$.\\n   - For $i=1$ to $99$: `out_any[i] = in[i] | in[i-1]`.\\n   - For $i=0$: The neighbor to the right (`in[-1]`) doesn\'t exist, so `out_any[0] = 0`.\\n\\n3. **`out_different` Logic:** Each bit `out_different[i]` indicates if `in[i]` is different from its neighbor to the left (`in[i+1]`), wrapping around. (Example: `out_different[98]` checks $in[98] \\neq in[99]$).\\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ XOR $in[i+1]$.\\n   - For $i=0$ to $98$: `out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[i+1]`.\\n   - For $i=99$ (wrap-around): The neighbor to the left is $in[0]$. So, `out_different[99] = in[99] ^ in[0]`.\\n\\n**Implementation Strategy:**\\nSince all required operations are purely combinational, we will use `assign` statements for maximal efficiency and clarity.\\n\\n**Syntax Error Advice:**\\n- **Array Indexing:** Be careful with array indexing when defining relationships. For example, `in[i+1]` must be valid. Since $i$ goes up to 99, $i+1$ can reach 100, which is out of bounds for `in[99:0]`. This is why we must explicitly handle the boundary conditions (i=99 for `out_both` and i=0 for `out_any`).\\n- **Concatenation vs. Slicing:** The hint warns against reverse slicing (`x[1:2]`). We will use direct indexing or concatenation `{in[i], in[i+1]}` if needed, but direct indexing is simplest here.\\n\\n**Refining Boundary Conditions for Code:**\\n\\n*   `out_both[99] = 1\'b0;`\\n*   `out_any[0] = 1\'b0;`\\n*   `out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[(i+1) % 100];` (This modulo operation elegantly handles the wrap-around for `out_different`.)\\n\\nWe can implement the non-wrapping parts using standard assignments and handle the wrap-around separately or use the modulo trick for all three, while explicitly setting the edge cases where the neighbor doesn\'t exist (like `out_both[99]` and `out_any[0]`).",\n    "module": "module TopModule (\\n    input  logic [99:0] in,\\n    output logic [99:0] out_both,\\n    output logic [99:0] out_any,\\n    output logic [99:0] out_different\\n);\\n\\n    // 1. out_both: out_both[i] = in[i] & in[i+1]. out_both[99] = 0.\\n    // For i = 0 to 98:\\n    assign out_both[0:98] = in[0:98] & in[1:99];\\n    assign out_both[99] = 1\'b0;\\n\\n    // 2. out_any: out_any[i] = in[i] | in[i-1]. out_any[0] = 0.\\n    // For i = 1 to 99:\\n    assign out_any[1:99] = in[1:99] | in[0:98];\\n    assign out_any[0] = 1\'b0;\\n\\n    // 3. out_different: out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[i+1] (wrapped).\\n    // We use the modulo operator to handle the wrap-around for i=99 (neighbor is in[0]).\\n    // Since Verilog/SystemVerilog allows arithmetic on array indices in some contexts, \\n    // we use a generator or conditional assignment for clarity and robustness.\\n    \\n    genvar i;\\n    generate\\n        for (i = 0; i < 100; i = i + 1) begin:\\n            // Calculate the index of the neighbor to the left (i+1, wrapped)\\n            localparam neighbor_index = (i + 1) % 100;\\n            \\n            // out_different[i] = in[i] XOR in[neighbor_index]\\n            assign out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[neighbor_index];\\n        end\\n    endgenerate\\n\\nendmodule"\n}')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nThe error below has been reported by the format tool:\n<format_error>\n{\n    "stdout": "",\n    "stderr": "./output_t22c_gemma4E4b_shard3b_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob092_gatesv100/rtl.sv:27: syntax error\\n./output_t22c_gemma4E4b_sh